    "recap_headline": "Long Beach State University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "LONG BEACH, Calif.\n\u2014 Long Beach State turned an early deficit into its most productive offensive night of the season Tuesday, scoring in eight of nine innings to defeat Loyola Marymount University 16-7 at Bohl Diamond at Blair Field. The Dirtbags finished with 14 hits, drew seven walks and reached 16 runs for the first time this season.\nSmith Chandler\nhighlighted the offensive surge with his first home run of the season, while\nTrevor Goldenetz\nand\nJake Evans\neach collected three hits and two RBI.\nTyler Gebb\nearned his first win of the year in relief, covering two innings and allowing just one unearned run as Long Beach State's bullpen helped secure the midweek victory.\nLMU came out quickly in the first inning, using four hits to build a 3-0 lead before the Dirtbags recorded an out on offense. Richie Klosek delivered the biggest early swing with a two-run triple after Andrew Mhoon's RBI single had already opened the scoring.\nLong Beach State answered immediately in the bottom half.\nTrevor Goldenetz\nled off with an infield bunt single, and\nJake Evans\nwas hit by a pitch before\nDylan Lina\ndrew a walk to load the bases.\nSmith Chandler\nthen worked a bases-loaded walk to bring home the first run, and\nMatt Toomey\nfollowed with a sacrifice fly to left, cutting the deficit to 3-2 before the inning ended with the tying run stranded.\nThe Dirtbags pulled even in the second after\nTy Borgogno\nsingled, and\nDamon Valdez's\nsacrifice bunt forced a throwing error that allowed Borgogno to reach third. Evans then lined an RBI single to shallow right, and moments later Valdez scored on a wild pitch to tie the game at 4-4.\nChandler pushed Long Beach State in front for good in the third inning, sending a leadoff homerun over the wall in deep center for his first home run of the season and a 5-3 lead.\nAfter\nDamon Valdez\nopened the fourth inning with a double to left field, Long Beach State continued to pressure the Lions by moving him to third on\nTrevor Goldenetz's\nsacrifice bunt, though LMU recorded the next two outs to keep the score at 5-3.\nThe Dirtbags added on again in the fifth when\nLuke Taylor\ndoubled home Toomey after catcher's interference extended the inning. Gebb took over on the mound in the top half and retired the side in order, helping preserve a 6-3 lead while earning his first victory of the season.\nLMU picked up an unearned run in the sixth. Goldenetz and Evans opened the inning with consecutive singles before\nDylan Lina\nlined a two-run single to left-center, restoring a four-run cushion at 8-4.\nLong Beach State added two more in the seventh when Valdez drove in Toomey with a groundout and Evans followed with another RBI single, extending the lead to 10-4.\nThe Lions briefly tightened the game in the eighth when Winfield Gurney hit a three-run homer to left, cutting the margin to 10-7, but the Dirtbags delivered their biggest inning of the season in response.\nThree walks and two hit batters fueled a six-run bottom of the eighth as\nLuke Taylor\nand Borgogno each forced in runs before Goldenetz lined a two-run single and\nTrotter Enright\nfollowed with a two-run double to left, stretching the lead to 16-7. The six-run frame gave Long Beach State its highest scoring output of the season.\nGebb,\nJoey Iglesias\n,\nKa'imi Kahalekai\nand\nErick Diez\ncombined to finish the final five innings, with Diez working a scoreless ninth to close out the win.\nLong Beach State returns to Big West play on the road this weekend against California State University, Bakersfield. First pitch for Friday's series opener is scheduled for 6:30 p.m. in Bakersfield as the Dirtbags look to build on their three-game winning streak."
  },
